So Descartes proposes that we should do this, but there's an individual at his time who's

51:00.800 --> 51:08.860
a contemporary of Descartes, who makes it explicit and radical, and then challenges

51:08.860 --> 51:13.500
Descartes with that radical derivation.

51:13.500 --> 51:21.900
Hobbes says, well, you know, all of this, what this means is that cognition is computation.

51:21.900 --> 51:26.180
Hobbes says that, he uses an older word, he says, rathiosination, what we would now say

51:26.180 --> 51:27.180
is cognition.

51:27.180 --> 51:29.780
By rathiosination I mean computation.

51:29.800 --> 51:31.680
Computation is computation.

51:31.680 --> 51:42.520
Now, there's a lot of people who were going to disagree with this model of computation.

51:42.520 --> 51:47.400
There's a lot of discussion right now, Brian Cantwell-Smith, a colleague of mine at the

51:47.400 --> 51:51.840
University of Toronto, does a lot of important work on the metaphysics of computation.

51:51.840 --> 51:55.200
I am not trying to state that this is the absolute truth about computation.

51:55.200 --> 51:58.080
That, of course, would be ironic, given what I just said about certainty.

51:58.100 --> 52:01.740
All I am arguing is, historically, this has been the interpretation of what computation

52:01.740 --> 52:04.340
was for people like Descartes and Hobbes.

52:04.340 --> 52:06.860
That's all we need for this argument.

52:06.860 --> 52:09.300
But Hobbes says, cognition is computation.

52:09.300 --> 52:12.300
And then here's the radical idea he proposes.

52:12.300 --> 52:19.660
He takes a new idea, current at the time, remember the idea that matter is a substance.

52:19.660 --> 52:25.780
Remember the old Aristotelian idea is matter is pure potential, but with Galileo, matter

52:25.800 --> 52:29.320
is a reality, right, in the sense of a substance.

52:29.320 --> 52:34.080
It resists, and it's good that it resists because I need something that resists my will

52:34.080 --> 52:36.800
in order to help me with my biases.

